      <dateline>VOORHEES</dateline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Judge Louis A Hornstine forbids two Political Action Committees from donating $10,000 to Democratic candidates for Voorhees Township Committee on grounds that township's long-time engineering consultant, Remington and Verdick, was using PAC to skirt $1,500 per candidate limit (New Jersey Daily Briefing) (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Charges that a corporation used a political action committee to get around campaign contribution limits are familiar at the national level. But they have also played a part in the race for the Voorhees Township Committee.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Charges that a corporation used a political action committee to get around campaign contribution limits are familiar at the national level. But they have also played a part in the race for the Voorhees Township Committee.</p>
        <p>Two weeks ago, a Superior Court judge forbade a $10,000 contribution that two PAC's had given to incumbent Democrats, finding that the committees' sole contributor -- the township's longtime engineering consultant, Remington and Verdick -- was using the PAC's to skirt a $1,500-per-candidate limit. Judge Louis A. Hornstine ordered that the money be given to charity.</p>
        <p>Democrats countered that the Republicans were getting illegal PAC money, too, but on Friday, Judge Hornstine refused to grant the Democrats' request to freeze the Republicans' PAC money. He scheduled a hearing on the issue for after the election.</p>
        <p>NEW JERSEY DAILY BRIEFING</p>
      </block>
